This deck was originally made by TeamSamurai on YouTube. Go and check out the video via the link I left for you. :)

This deck is a bit complicated for my understanding, but basically the goal is to put your Skull Servant monsters in the Graveyard in order to deal insane amounts of damage with your "King of the Skull Servants" card.

While before my "Magesty with Eyes of Blue" deck (Featuring "Blue-Eyes White Dragon of course") was my most expensive deck, featuring an insane price of $109.00, this deck takes the new crown in terms of most expensive deck of mine, with an absolutely sickenning cost of $317.41. I will try to make my decks cheaper in the future.

If you have any feedback, comments, or recommendations, know that it is welcome. :)

deck_excerpt: Bring a mask or become a tribute to the doomed!
deck_description:
The Dark Pandemic (Erectti's Deck #13)

A Lair of Darkness deck that allows you to tribute your opponent's monsters to activate powerful effects. Crush your opponents by using overwhelming control cards like Gozen Match to only allow Dark monsters to be summoned, Virus tech cards to infect your opponent's hand and deck, and Super Polymerization to fusion summon powerful creatures using your opponent's monsters! If you thought the COVID-19 Pandemic was bad, then you better bring a mask for this deck! 

Feedback is appreciated!

Hello all,

 

Blue-Eyes has had a problem being consistent for quite a while. So I sat down and created a version that makes the deck at least a little bit better. It's also a lot of fun and can keep up with the other decks in smaller tournaments. In the video you can see everything that is important but I summarize again what the "combos" are.

 

Psychic End Punisher  : With Piri Reis Map  you look for Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring  and normal summon her (yep, totally cringe) and use a blue-eyes which you can easily get out and go for Psychic End Punisher . Since you have to pay half your LP with Piri Reis Map  is punsiher benefits from it.

 

Chaos Engine: You use this engine for link climbing. You use Black Dragon Collapserpent  or White Dragon Wyverburster  for Striker Dragon  to find the counterpart afterwards. With these counterpart and Striker Dragon  you go mostly on Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres .

 

The rest should be very understandable. :)

 

If you like the decklist or the video feel free to leave a like and if you want to support me feel free to leave a subscription. :)

kurze Erklärung was hier abgeht:

Mikanko's leiten den eigenen Kampfschaden an denn Gegner weiter, wenn sie mit Equip-Spells ausgerüstet sind. Für 8000 LP benötigt man bei Lava Golem oder den beiden Kaijus 3 Angriffe. Es können somit alle Kaijus gespielt werden die Mehr als 2667 ATK haben.
Die wahl fiel hierbei auf Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju und Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju. Gardarla für Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds und Radian für Majesty's Fiend (Runic Stun).

Waking the Dragon ist nur nen filler es kann hier auch Pot of Extravagance gespielt werden.

eine andere Deckversion mit Double-Edged Sword ist hier zu finden: Mikanko Fun (neues Fenster)

zur Erklärung der Karten:

Ohime the Manifested Mikanko sucht eine Mikanko-Karte, anschließend muss eine Karte abgeworfen werden. Sie kann mit Preparation of Rites gesucht werden.
Mikanko Water Arabesque und Mikanko Fire Dance (Karten lesen könnt ihr selbst) beschwört die Mikankos (Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko / Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko) Erstere Sucht einen Mikanko-EquipSpell, letztere ist für den Fall der Fälle. Die beiden Equip-Spells können zudem mit Hidden Armory gescuht werden, da keine Normalbeschwörung benötigt wird.
The Great Mikanko Ceremony beschwört z.B. Ohime the Manifested Mikanko 
Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko ist für den 3. Angriff und etwas Schutz

some Plays:

-> Vorraussetzung ist Gegner hat ein Monster mit >= 2000 ATK (sonst Kaiju / Lava Golem)

Du hast: Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko, Ohime the Manifested Mikanko + Mikanko mit Equip-Spell (hier Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko mit Mikanko Water Arabesque)

1st Attack mit Ha-Re
2nd Attack mit Ohime -> Eff Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko um Mikanko Water Arabesque vom Feld zu senden
3rd Attack mit Ohime -> im BattleStep Quick-Eff von Ohime um Arabesque an Ha-Re vom GY zu equippen -> Eff Gate um Mikanko Water Arabesque vom Feld zu senden
4th Attack mit Ohime, da Gate keinen OPT hat 

Ohime hat den DMG-Eff. der Mikankos, nur ohne die Equip-Bedingung



-> Vorraussetzung ist nun Gegner hat ein Monster mit >= 2667 ATK (sonst Kaiju / Lava Golem)

Du hast: Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko + 2 Mikanko mit Equip-Spell (Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko oder Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko mit Mikanko Water Arabesque und Mikanko Fire Dance)

1st Attack mit irgend einer Mikanko (hier Ha-Re the Sword Mikanko)*
2nd Attack mit der anderen Mikanko (hier Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko) -> Eff Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko um Equip-Spell der ersten Mikanko (Ha-Re) vom Feld zu senden
3rd Attack mit Ni-Ni

*zu den Angriffen: wenn Ha-Re und Ni-Ni auf dem Feld sind immer mit Ni-Ni als 2. und 3. angreifen, damit sie ihren Equip-Spell behält. Sie hat im gegnerischen Zug einen nützlichen Quick Eff. (Ni-Ni the Mirror Mikanko) 

 

Going First:

-> is kacke aber haben ja zum Glück ne Going First Meta
Versuch an Mikanko Promise zu kommen. Setz das zur Not mit Trap Trick. Durch Heavenly Gate of the Mikanko müssen zudem gegnerische Monster deine Mikankos mit Equip-Spells angreifen.

deck_excerpt: Cocantorium can Name-Change and Summon itself from GY
deck_description:
Made for Domain Format, a format with a deckmaster   https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

I think of this deck as a bird repeatly eatting its friends from deck. Won't you join me in that thought? 
The deckmaster, the card that we will have indefinite access to until we are out of the Domain Game, is Cocatorium the Heavy Metal Avian 
It banishes a card from ~~~Deck~~~ to copy its name, attribute, type, and level! Let the Shinnagins begin!

So, eat the Zoodiac, gain the name and reap the benefits of Zoodiac Broadbull all to yourself! Add the Tri-Brigade Fraktall and combo off with one card! (Use Zoodiac Chakanine to reborn and link into Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom to summon Fraktall)

Eat the Spiritual Beast Rampengu, trick the tamers into thinking you're one of their own so they can give you Ritual Beast Steeds and Ritual Beast Ambush . You'll only need to Normal summon out any Ritual Beast Tamer and you can use it with Cocatorium to Contact Fuse into Ritual Beast Ulti-Cannahawk ! (Loop it 4 times the Ritual Beast way to add 4 cards!)

Devour the Scareclaw card, to Link Summon into a Scareclaw Light-Heart adding the Primitive Planet Reichphobia ! Voila, you've ensured access to a removal of an opponent's card this turn and further turns as well!

Set the migrating Birds on a journey through the Stomach, putting Floowandereeze & Robina  in rotation to be added to hand the next time you normal summon your Deckmaster (but you cannot Special Summon the turn you do). We all know how persistant Floowandereeze is, the advantages they bring!

The Ancient Warriors strom into play, with big powerful statlines and amazing board clearing effects, all you need to get them started is to summon or impersonate a Ancient Warriors - Virtuous Liu Xuan ! As a Wind-attribute Ancient Warrior, Link into the Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords for the ablity to add any "Ancient Warrior" Card to hand and combo ~

Have Fun eating your allys -

Cocatorium the Kirby

deck_excerpt: Raye seems to be Konami's favourite girl lately... Blind-Second Sky Striker takes advantage of it!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

Who is gonna win? Gigantic Fusion Dragons, Mechanical of Armies, Masters of the Arcane Arts, or a single girl in a mech suit? My money is on Raye, since she is more powerful than ever with an arsenal of blind second cards, handtraps and staples!


Now in 2023, Raye is powered up in Masterduel with the introduction of Therion Regulus (free 2800ATK beatstick + negate) and Linkage (Extra starter/OTK with 8000DMG)!

Raye seems to be Konami's favourite girl, since the banlist also unleashed a second Kagari which vastly increases the Sky Striker grind game. Also, we got some pretty nifty main page art and icon border. It feels good to be a Striker main in 2023! Thanks Komoney :3


The philosophy with blind second Sky Strikers is to destroy most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's unparalleled grind game.

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Hi all, 

It's been a while since I would build a Prank-Kids list. Despite the Prank-Kids Meow-Meow-Mu ban in May 2022, I stay convinced that this deck is sitll good (the strategy is just slower than before). For the deckbuilding, I decided to focus the deck on the Fusion Summoning. And as I'm not a huge fan of the Invoked splash (it's still a good add to improve the Fusion strategy), I tried to build a pure version for this metagame. I also decided to play a classic 40-card list (without splashing a Adventure package).

Card Alternatives

If you want to change littles things in the list, I see some tech cards to include:

  • Link into the VRAINS! : this card is nut in the deck! I This card is able to accelerate the Prank-Kids strategy by accessing faster to your Link-2 monsters (RIP Meow-Meow).
  • Reasoning : I don't really like this card. However, this bring a little more consistency in the deck
  • Handtraps like D.D. Crow or other good cards in the current meta. I already made the choice to use Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Infinite Impermanence which are for me, the more generic handtraps for decks with graveyard interactions.

 

If you have feedbacks and improvements for this deck, don't hesitate to share it in the comments :)

Have fun guys!

Watch As The Ounce Phantoms Of Beasts Reborn Into High And Mighty Jets And Planes

This Deck is more Lyrilusc Tri-Brigade rather than a Tri-Brigade Deck splashing a Lyrilusc engine. Since Recital Starling is currently Semi-Limited (and will probably be Unlimited soon), Tri Lyrilusc looks decent, especially with Tri-Brigade Roar coming in CYAC. 

3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 3 D.D. Crow. Crow is nice because it is a handtrap and it is a Level 1 Winged Beast which is really nice for Lyrilusc plays if necessary. 3 Tri-Brigade Fraktall, 2 Tri-Brigade Kerass, and 3 Tri-Brigade Nervall. These are basically just here to help you Link climb into Apollousa, but Nerval being a Level 1 Winged Beast synergizes nicely with the Lyrilusc cards. 3 Lyrilusc - Turquoise Warbler. It's a good free Summon on an empty board and it can get out another Lyrilusc for free if it is Specialed. 3 Lyrilusc - Sapphire Swallow. You can cut it to 2 if you want, but since it basically gives you two Level 1's on the field if you control a Winged Beast, it's pretty nice to open. 3 Lyrilusc - Beryl Canary. This gives you access to Ensemblue Robin after you are done with your Link plays and it is nice for making Zeus as a follow-up. 3 Lyrilusc - Cobalt Sparrow. This card searches any Level 1 Winged Beast on Special including itself. 2 Lyrilusc - Celestine Wagtail. It can search Bird Call on Special for extension or for follow-up and it can give Ensemblue Robin an extra material for another bounce. 

1 Foolish Burial, 3 Lyrilusc - Bird Call which is so broken, 1 Called by the Grave, 3 Fire Formation - Tenki, and 3 Tri-Brigade Roar. If you control any Link monster, you can use Roar to send Shuraig from your Extra Deck to the GY to just search any missing combo piece you need either for extension or follow-up.

Extra Deck: 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Downerd Magician, 1 Number F0: Utopic Draco Future, 1 Number F0: Utopic Future. 2 Lyrilusc - Recital Starling. You only need to play 2 since that's enough material for F0 and you are never making more than 2 in your starting combo either way. 1 Lyrilusc - Ensemblue Robin which is as many bounces as it has Material. 1 Lyrilusc - Assembled Nightingale which is a direct attacker to make Zeus. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, 2 Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen since you can make it turn 3 for removal or you can send it off of Roar, 1 Tri-Brigade Rugal the Silver Sheller which can also be replaced with Hraesvelgr the Desperate Doom Eagle but Rugal is easier to Summon generically, 1 Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom, 1 Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords, and 1 Salamangreat Almiraj. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kaijus, 1 Droll & Lock Bird as a Crossout target, 3 Crossout Designator which you have your targets being Ash, Crow, Nibiru, Droll, and Imperm, 3 Cosmic Cyclone, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

deck_description: You can use bystials to go into wollow to potentially stop tears from starting their combo.

Because of Feb 2023 banlist, I will retire this deck.
Fusion focus but have Ghoti as a secondary engine against Dimension Shifter, and I can't afford 3 Perlereino. 

Tips: 

Ishizu Tear is RNG, so just plays with whatever you mills, but I like the mill 8 combo with Kitkallos. Fusion for Kitkallos and effect to search Merli, and activate Kit 2nd effect to summon Merli and both effect with mill 8. 

Stuff to keep in mind, Ghoti plays can consistently be access through Spright Elf, and if Deepest Depths in graveyard, then you can extend the play to search for Ixeep or Snopios as materials for Synchro or XYZ. 

You can remove Kashira Ogre for other Kashtira names or Bystial, I just put it in because my friends plays a lot of floodgates and Orge is a common rarity. 

Things that can be side out: 

2 Leaffish ||1 Tear Sulliek || 1 Kashtira Preparations || 1 Kashtira Ogre || 1 Tear Scream || 1 Paces  || 2 Ghost Sister || 1 Tear Grief
Bagooska/Abyss Dweller can be swap for one or both of the Ghoti Synchro so you have to have more plays because the first Ghoti Deep Beyond can be negated. 

Future updates: 

Getting 3 Tearlaments Kashtira and 3 Baldrake after Photon Hypernova drop.

deck_excerpt: "The blood of our enemies is still the blood of men. The real glory is to spare it."
deck_description:
This deck is designed to drain your opponent's LifePoints while holding them back with silly little spells and traps.

Basically, the card "Bad Reaction to Shimochi" makes it so that each time your opponent were to gain LifePoints, it would be negated, and they would instead LOSE that same amount of LifePoints. Combo this with the card "Gift Card" which gives your opponents 3,000 LP. So just by activating 2 "Gift Card"s while "Bad Reaction to Shimochi" is on the field can kill and opponent. This also combos with "Dark Cure", as each time your opponent would summon a monster, they gain LP equal to half of its ATK. So just by playing the game, they're losing.

Next, you'll want to activate your "Dark Room of Nightmare" card. This will make it so that each time your opponent would take damage from a card effect, they take 300 more points of damage. This stacks with every single damage-dealing effect in this deck. This includes "Mask of Despell", which equips to an opponents' spell card, and each time their turn starts while that card is in play, they take 500 damage. 

There is a card called "Coffin Seller", which deals 300 points of damage each time a monster is sent to their graveyard. This stacks with "Dark Room of Nightmare", making that damage 600.

 

To sum it all up, this deck is built to stall your opponent and force them to take thousands of damage just for having a turn. If you have any recommendations, let me know in the comments.

deck_excerpt: The most fun way to play this deck IMO
deck_description: The most fun way to play this deck IMO
Have not played it
Branded Gears

Think I'm neat? Think this deck is shit? Hit me up @ https://twitter.com/DiceQueenDi or https://www.twitch.tv/dicequeendi

Intro

Hello! This was my first deck and something I worked out / built all on my own. I actually picked up Yugioh MD only a month ago and only picked Weather Hackers cause it was the first card I pulled and goddamn Rainbow is one hellava waifu. Using this I got into Plat within a couple weeks.

Anyways. This is called the 'Adventure Kit' as this is the version of the deck splashing the Adventure Token engine. While the Painters don't have a lot of synergy with Adventurers, they both want to do the same thing: set up negates and bounces and completely dick over the enemy. I truly believe that Weather Painters are one of the few archetypes that DON'T need handtraps.

I REPEAT: WEATHER PAINTER DECKS DON'T NEED HANDTRAPS.

Most of the time you can just completely play through an Ash or a Maxx C (especially since your main deal is double normal summoning with Forecast) since you have SO MANY SEARCHERS in this version of the deck. With the Adventure engine, you have not only an ally looking to do everything you already want to do, but an alternate win condition if your Painters are having difficulty setting up.

 

Strategies and Notes

Weather Painters: Standard painter plays. Throw out Rainbow on turn 1, Moonbow if you're turn 2 to disrupt boards. You're literally rushing to have your negates and floodgates out and just completely dick over the enemy. If you can set up Skill Drain OR Rainbow you can basically win the game. Note I say or cause while painters can completely swerve around Skill Drain (a required part of the deck), it'll negate Rainbows/Moonbow giving the negate/bounce banish to their painters. Anyways as a standard painter, you just floodgate the enemy, bounce back their bois (since Thundery Canvas is a NON-TARGETING bounce), then beat them down. You can even use your Painters to trigger Torrential Tribute, then trigger their abilities to get them off the board for a free board wipe + canvas effects.

Best turn: Cloudy Canvas -> Snow Painter into Rainbowed Canvas -> trigger Canvas to get Forecast -> Forecast into any weather spell/trap -> Forecast double summon into Cloudy -> Forecast spell/traps into Rainbow/Moonbow -> bring back Cloudy/Rainbow canvas with Cloudy. Next turn you'll have 2 negates on boards, or three if you can summon with Rainbow Canvas.

You DESPERATELY need Snow Painter in your starting hand. If you're lucky, Piri can help get you into her. Feeling super anxious? Slot in more Piris.

 

Adventurers: Standard adventurer plays. Get out your negate or your double bouncer out with token and literally make the enemy's life a living hell. IMPORTANT NOTE: Weather Painters DESPERATELY needs you to know how to form your board. You want to keep your painters/adventurers on two opposite sides of the field. As FAR AWAY FROM EACH OTHER AS POSSIBLE. If you cross over the lines at all you're going to screw yourself over.

The best card here aside from Griffon's omni negate is Illegal Knight. Use Illegal Knight to bounce two cards for free (like labyrinth traps :3) then use Dracoback to bounce it back into your hand. BAM. Free.

 

Magician Souls: Consider these your Janitors, your Handymen, your Glue. Magician Souls is an extremely strong tech choice for both painters and adventurers, as you will eventually run into dead cards stuck on your field or in your hand. For example: if you can't draw the Painter monsters, or if your adventurer engine is dead.

Fun Interactions: you can throw out Dracoback for a free re-equip onto the token, or your canvases (with cloudy on the board) to recycle ones you might have lost earlier. Plus! Both Thundery and Magician Souls can send Skill Negate as cost, so you can turn it off whenever you want! If dealing with big mons, or anyone else super unfortunate to put a fat boy on the wrong parts of the field, Magician Souls can turn into Linkuriboh for a stall or Relinquished Anima for a major punish.

 

Lava Golem: Lava Golem gets its own special category as it interacts with both Weather Painters and Adventurers in a savage way. It's not a CRITICAL strategy, but when it appears on the right board you've got a free win with the insanely powerful removal it has. You can also slot in Kaijus or Nibiru, but Lava has a lot more options.

LG Thundery Canvas: wipes 2 mons, then bounce back to hand and wipe two more if you can.

LG Moonbow: bounce Golem every standby, and you have a CONSTANT 1k/turn burn that your opponent can't deal with, since you can chain Moonbow's banish on the damage tick. They can't tribute, can't link it, can't remove or banish it... They have to deal with Moonbow itself.

LG Adventurers: just like Thundery Canvas, but even stronger. Lava Golem 2 mons -> Illegal Knight bouncing Lava Golem + 1 other card + Lava Golem 2 more (even Illegal Knight if you REALLY wanna) for what accounts for a tribute Raigeki. That or, LG, Dracoback, LG, IK for 5 mons if you wanna lose your IK.

 

Links: Topological Bomber Dragon, Borrelsword Dragon, Accesscode Talker, Underworld Goddess, and either Knightmare Phoenix or Cerberus. You have really strong board bounces/wipes so I lean on Phoenix, but go whatever. The rest are tech choices, but I'm personally fond of Kiryu Coco-- I mean Topological Bomber. Remember the Torrential Tribute trick with Painters? Think that but EVERY TURN. If you have Adventure Token on board and are willing to sac your Illegal Knight you can also just interrupt nuke both fields.

Lyna is here too I guess, but it's mostly here to pull out fodder for TBD, or pull out a dangerous card sitting in your opponent's GY. You COULD maybe swap out 1 Thundery Painter for a Rain Painter and Lyna for Eria then battle sacc it as an alternative way to pull out Water Enchantress... But that'd be stupid... Unless...

 

XYZs: You will almost NEVER use these and will most likely just use them as pot fodder. However, they can come in serious clutch if you're in a corner and need to stall by limiting attacks, or just being resistant to getting deleted.

 

Side Deck: this is just filled with cards you can probably just slot into the deck if you'd like. You can get rid of the Adventure package for a more classic deck, but I find removing em for handtraps unnecessary. Also, Cerberus is good for monster removal if you wanna get rid of Phoenix.

Side spells: You also don't really need terraforming since it just pulls out Forecast, which won't necessarily nab you a painter to use it :T. Raigeki/Feather for wipes, Twin Twisters if you find your hand filled with dead cards often. Dark Ruler no more is absolutely boss at the right time, but not necessary since you typically have like 4 omni negates floating around.

Side traps: You can swap out the Torrential Tributes with any combination of these. If you're getting rid of the Adventure package, definitely bring in Anti-Spell Fragrance, as it'll cripple most decks (especially runicks). I don't recommend Rivalry of Warlords unless you're going PURE Painters as it'll just screw you over in the long run.

 

Final Words

Weather Painters is an extremely strong rogue deck if you're able to set up. Adventurers are really strong if you can't get out the Painters and are looking to stall/work an alternate beatdown win-condition. You will usually not have BOTH online at the same time. Consider it like switching between the two styles as both Weather Painters and Adventurers both contain one-card combo starters. 

Your most important cards: Snow Painter, Water Enchantress, Rite of Aramesir, Fateful Adventure, Piri Map, and Foolish Burial. That's literally 9/42 cards, or a 21.4% of the deck can start a one-card combo. Again, if you're feeling anxious, slot in a couple more Piri's. You can also eke out Snow with literally any Painter + Cloudy/Rainbowed canvas, or slip into them with Magician Souls or Pot of Prosperity.

The deck has an extreme amount of consistency, provided you know what you're doing.
Insane

deck_description: Nothing too special. Lightsworn relies on high-rolling pretty heavily, but the simple addition of just one Phantom of Chaos and one Monster Reincarnation is absolutely insane for the deck. It allows you to use basically any effect you want, including Judgement Dragon, as long as you have that card in the GY. This is comes up rather often, especially in the mid / late-game, but if you happen to ditch a JD early on and Normal Summon the Phantom, it can be game-ending. It allows for a second use of basically anything in the deck, from Lumina to gain a board presence back, Ehren to out a sneaky facedown, Chaos Sorcerer to out an annoying card, a Tragoedia for funny plays, or a Card Trooper for quick mills. Otherwise pretty standard.

deck_excerpt: "It's better to be feared than loved."
deck_description:
Give your Opponent's Zoophobia as they face-off against this deck!

Main Deck:

Part 1: The Monsters

Chapter 1: Phobophobia (Scareclaws)

"All level 3 and 4 Scareclaw monsters share the effect "You can Special Summon this card (from your hand) to your Main Monster Zone, adjacent to a "Scareclaw" monster you control or in its column. You can only Special Summon "Scareclaw Astra" once per turn this way."

  • Scareclaw Reichheart - Is your S/T searcher, and when you have 3 defense position monsters it gives you a draw. This is the guy you want to search using Primitive Planet Reichphobia as he searches your negate in Scareclaw Sclash .
  • Scareclaw Acro - Gives your Scareclaw monsters in the Extra monster zone a 300 ATK boost for each defense position monster you control.
  • Scareclaw Astra - Gives your Scareclaw monsters in the Extra monster zone extra attacks for each differently named Scareclaw monster you control in defense position (Max 5)
  • Scareclaw Belone - Gives your Scareclaw monsters in the Extra monster zone the ability to do piercing damage.

The best ones to have in your endboard in my opinion is Acro with either Astra or Belone since they help push for OTK which is what you are aiming for most of the time with the Deck.

Chapter 2: Erythrophobia (Kashtira)

Scareclaws received their own Kashtirafied monster in the form of the creatively Scareclaw Kashtira (which should have been called Cerberus IMO) so thats why I am using a small Kash pack that consists of:

  • 3x Kashtira Unicorn - Searches Kashtiratheosis which is full Kash Combo and gives free extension with Kashtira Birth , I run it at 3 because its the most important piece of the engine here.
  • 2x Kashtira Fenrir - You really just want to summon this guy to get Kashtira Riseheart or Scareclaw Kashtira to push for OTK, since you will rarely be pulling off his effect by declaring an attack, due to Tri-Heart's floodgate effect.
  • 1x Kashtira Riseheart - Only use is to go into Kashtira Arise-Heart .
  • 1x Scareclaw Kashtira - Free extension in case your cards die and its effect to attack in defense position really helps the deck to OTK, while also having the ability to negate the effect of monsters your "Scareclaws" and "Kashtira" battle against, if you banish a Kash in grave you can bring them back later with Kashtira Birth .
  • 1x Kashtira Shangri-Ira and Kashtira Arise-Heart - I don't think these guys need that much of an introduction but, Zone blocking and free summon from deck and Macro Cosmos on leg with a banish face-down by detatching effect. The floodgate effect of Arise doesnt hurt the deck since you wont be going into anything with your Scareclaws most of the time, and even then you can just attach them as materials to this guy so they go back to the grave once Arise dies.

The only other monster you run is Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju because its the Kaiju with the lowest defense, which is easier for Scareclaw Tri-Heart to run over while also giving you a way to remove Tower-likes and problematic monsters.

Chapter 2:

Part 1: Rhabdophobia (Spells/Traps)

  • Scareclaw Arrival - Having the same joke as The Arrival Cyberse @Ignister , Nova/Arrival is a Non-Opt revival of either Visas or another Scareclaw which caused some Tearlament lists to run Scareclaws as an engine. This card is normally used to either go into Scareclaw Tri-Heart in case you got a bad hand or to OTK.
  • Primitive Planet Reichphobia and Pressured Planet Wraitsoth - Both allow you to search a monster from their respective archetypes Scareclaw and Kashtira, Reichnophobia is the one you want to keep on the field, it causes your opponent's monsters to lose ATK/DEF helping with the OTK and if there are 3 monsters anywhere in defense position you can pop a card in the field, removing threats like backrow after you Dark Ruler No More , Lightning Storm or Alpha, the Master of Beasts .
  • Scareclaw Straddle - Attack boost and " Called by the Grave " in a pinch.
  • Kashtiratheosis and Kashtira Birth - Card you want to get out of Kashtira Unicorn the turn you summon him to go full combo, and extension and way to summon the Kashtiras in hand after you set your board up.
  • Super Polymerization - Free removal! featuring Garura, Wings of Resonant Life , Starving Venom Fusion Dragon and Mudragon of the Swamp from the Generic Super Poly targets Series!
  • Scareclaw Twinsaw and Scareclaw Sclash - Icarus attack that shuts down links for a turn which comes up if your opponent tries to accesscode your bum and free Omni-Negate if you control a Scareclaw Link in the EMZ respectively.

Chapter 3:

Part 1: Teraphobia (Scareclaw Links)

  • Scareclaw Light-Heart - Searches Primitive Planet Reichphobia , Very Very important at 3 for the grind gamessince if it resolves its a free archetypal search with the field.
  • Scareclaw Tri-Heart - Behold! your end-goal. Changes all monsters to defense position and is unnafected by the effects of those defense position monsters, it can also revive a LV3 Scareclaw which then he lets you add a Scareclaw monster from your deck. It should be noted using the last effect will lock you into Scareclaws for the rest of your turn. Incredibly annoying floodgate for some decks to out, and thats why Kashtiras, Saw and Sclash are so important, because they shut-off the only weakness of the Deck, Links monsters.

Example of a Combo: (Unicorn, any LV3 Scareclaw and Reich in hand)

SS Kashtira Unicorn > Search Kashtiratheosis , Normal summon Scareclaw Reichheart > Add Scareclaw Sclash , Link Scareclaw Reichheart into Scareclaw Light-Heart > Search Primitive Planet Reichphobia > Add any LV3 Scareclaw, Summon both that monster and the Scareclaw in hand to the adjacent zones and go into Scareclaw Tri-Heart , Activate Kashtiratheosis summoning Kashtira Fenrir from deck, Kashtira Fenrir adds Kashtira Riseheart , Fenrir and Unicorn XYZ into Kashtira Shangri-Ira , activate Rise in hand, this will trigger Shang and will let you use the Rise to make Kashtira Arise-Heart . Now you can revive a dead Scareclaw with Scareclaw Tri-Heart and add another one. 

So you end on a Floodgate, Omni negate, Zone locker which will summon Fenrir next turn from deck and a Macro cosmos with target face-down banish.

Note: It has come to my attention that Sclash cant be send to the GY under Arise, so in that case you should end on twin-saw)

Try making a deck where Laundry can join.
She can mill, so...

3 negates at max.
Best field result:
• 3+ negates (Dragonmaid Sheou, Tearlaments Rulkallos, Tearlaments Sulliek, then fusion Dragonmaid House with any Tearlaments for Predaplant Dragostapelia for the 4th) 
• 1 counter normal summon (using Dragonmaid Tidying)

Note:
• Can play more Ishizu, or handtraps.
• Incompleted Side Deck => Side Deck is optional.

Theorycrafting deck.

Have been testing against Madolche Vernusylph Ishizu, Spright Melffy, pure Evil★Twin with 50+% winrate.
Using Evil★Twin as main core, with Bystial (Byssted) as supporting elements.

Main goal on first turn is to have on the field (if possible) Evil★Twin Trouble Sunny, Bystial Lubellion, Branded Regained (and Branded Beast, for the best field).

How to:
• After successfully summon Evil★Twin Trouble Sunny, send Bystial Lubellion, add Bystial Magnamhut;
• Special summon Bystial Magnamhut by banishing 1 Live★Twin;
• Tributing Magnamhut for Lubellion > add Branded Regained.

Note:
• Some cards can be replaced up to players' favors (Raigeki, Ash Blossom, Unchained Abomination, Nightmare Gryphon, practically any cards in Side Deck)

deck_excerpt: Branded Bystial Post PHN ( Banish man format )
deck_description:
Hello everyone this is Lohamora again, with my 2nd, Top 6 decks post photon hypernova, before going to the deck list, make sure to check my first Top 6 deck, which was Witchcrafters ( still feels great to see Witchcrafters consistent ), and now let's get started 

here are some explanations and notes

 Main deck

Bystial Lubellion: well the best targets to search with him would be Bystial Magnamhut but if you had any other Bystials in your hand, you better search Bystial Saronir which helps your combos such as sending Branded Retribution to add any branded spell/trap from your GY to your hand or Branded Regained which can be placed on spell/trap zone by the effect of Branded Beast during the end phase, one last thing I can note here is Placing spell/traps to your spell/trap zones does not means Activating them, so even Anti-spell Fragrance can't stop it.

Fusion Deployment: I call this card life saver, cuz it's so crazy, especially in this deck, you can reveal Grand-Guignol from your extra deck to special summon Blazing Cartesia directly from your deck which helps to play around Imperm or effect veiler whenever you ns or ss Aluber to search for any branded spell/traps, you can also make Grand-guignol with Cartesia and Aluber, I'll take this any of the days.

The allure of Darkness + Despian Tragedy: this deck doesn't have that much draw power, so adding allure with tragedy, won't even make this neg 1, that's why I like this card, it also gives you 4 free spots to use your side deck cards, instead of them.
 
Branded expulsion: I would say the most broken card post photon hypernova, you see summoning your banished Fallen of Albaz during your opponent's turn in their sensitive combo moments is pretty devilish, ah you also don't need to be worried about the discard effect, cuz you get to recycle Blazing Cartesia during the End phase of your turn, as for more information check out the combo lines.

Tri-brigade Mercourier: I don't know how many of you know this, but Mercourier can use its effect even if it's on the field so another good target to special summon it back with branded expulsion 

Super polymerization:  the best board breaker in the game, Graura, and Mudragon are indeed the best targets for this card, Mudragon is great against Kashtira. 

Extra deck 

Rindburmm the Striking dragon: one of the craziest fusion monsters, which can negate any fusion/synchro/XYZ/link monsters effect then you can return one monster on the field to your hand, this can also negate your own Extra monsters effects, which helps a lot, let's say, you used your own mirrorjade then send a fusion monster that lists Fallen of Albaz as its materials as a cost, to banish one monster on the field, you can use Rindburmm to negate your own mirror jade, and there you go you still have an unused Mirrorjade effect, and a Search effect during the end phase, if you send Albion the branded dragon, but wait this card does more than that, Let's say, your opponent used Dark ruler no more after the effect resolves you can tribute your Rindburmm with Branded expulsion to ss your banished Fallen of Albaz, then use Albaz to fusion summon by using your opponent's monster, after that you can Rindburmm effect in the GY, to banish the Fallen of Albaz you just used for fusion summoning, to revive back the Rindburmm, and there you go, Dark ruler no more didn't do anything special, now how to make this card, well with branded fusion, just send Tri-brigade mercourier with Fallen of Albaz, then Banish your Tri-brigade mercourier with the Effect of any Bystial monsters, to search for any monster card that lists Fallen of Albaz, which in this case it's Blazing Cartesia but if you had any other ways to ss her like with the effect of Fusion deployment, you can add Albion the Shrouded dragon, use it to send Branded regained to place it on the field with the effect of Branded Beast or to send Branded retirbution or Branded in white, which combo you prefer to be honest.

Grand-Guignol the Dusk Dragon: again another crazy fusion monster, which can be made with Blazing Cartesia and any light or dark monsters, this card is like a combo completer, well there are 2 main combos with this card, the first one is to send Albion the branded dragon to set branded expulsion from your deck, and your end board will be: Rindburmm + Grand-Guignol + Bystial lubellion + branded regained + branded beast + branded expulsion, which by far it's maximum 5 interruptions, and the second one is sending both Branded retribution and branded in white to the GY, by the help of Bystial Saronir and Albion the shrouded dragon and in this case grand-guignol can send any of your missing peace, let's say you send Branded retribution to the GY with Bystial Saronir effect, in this case you will Send Albion the shrouded dragon to the GY, with grand-guidnol effect, then use Albion the shrouded dragon, to send Branded in white, then use Retribution to add branded in white from your GY, then your end board is going to be: Rindburmm + Grand-guignol + branded beast + Bystial lubellion + Mirrorjade + Branded in Red, which is by far 7 interruptions, but the second combo can't happen all the time, just like first combo, but when it happens, your dear opponent goes R.I.P ( lmao ), but wait there is still more, if a monster is special summoned by the your opponent activated monster effect, you can banish this card from you GY or field to ss a dogmatika monster from your deck or a despian monster from your extra deck, which in post photon hypernova we have 2 targets Despian Quaerities or Despain Proskenion, you decide which one to use, i chose the Quaerities.

Side deck 

Book of the eclipse: This card is broken in the decks and can get rid of face-down monsters, before the end phase like Branded Bystial - Exosister - Kashtira - etc..., It is also the best counter for annoying pure Kashtira deck.

Triple tasking and Triple Talents: the best cards for going first after losing game 1, they are surely helpful

Lava golem: I'm not saying we don't normal summon in this deck, but sometimes, we don't even normal summon, again you decide if you want to play lava golem or Kashtira Fenrir, ( Fenrir just has a conflict with Bystial cards sometimes )


HOW TO SIDE IN THIS DECK ??
 this is how I do cut all 3 allure of darkness + 1 Despain tragedy + 1 Fusion deployment + 1 super poly + 1 Bystial Magnamhut or Ad libitum of Despia ( depending on the deck you are facing against ) and at some points, you can even cut branded in white and branded retributions if you are good with the first combo line which I explained in Grand-Guidnol section, here you got 9 side deck space.

Thank you, guys, for reading, also this was Branded Bystial deck POST PHOTON HYPERNOVE, this deck will get way better again, once we get  new cards in CYBER STORM ACCEL, be honest I didn't expect a happy ending, I'm glad lore didn't end up sad ( Stigmatika forever )

Well see you guys in my next top 6 decks post photon hypernova ( Spoiler it's Thunder water ball deck ) and yes I'm keeping Kashtira deck profile for the last cuz it's the number 1 best deck in banish man format.

CYA

deck_excerpt: A budget-focused take on (Crystal Beast) Conclave Control
deck_description:
Conclave Control is the most playable form that Crystal Beasts have taken in years, and it's not hard to see why. Between Sapphire Pegasus, Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon, and the new support from the structure deck, this deck takes advantage of a frankly unbelievable advantage engine that ends on a board of Bagooska, Necrovalley (or Zombie World), and some backrow. The end goal is to floodgate your opponent out of the game with Bagooska and your field spell of choice while keeping your opponent off of monsters using Crystal Conclave.

The Extra Deck is a highly-customizable toolbox with few absolute essentials outside of Bagooska and Abyss Dweller, allowing this deck to use and abuse Pot of Extravagance very easily. Outside of the two aforementioned monsters, the deck easily takes advantage of the R4NK toolbox, as well as many generic Links such as the Knightmares. Explosive game-enders such as Borrelsword Dragon (i.e. Accesscode Talker at home) and the Numeron Dragon package are just the cherry on top.

This deck is built at merging dragons and magicains with some link monster s to surrpass other decks. And using power full fusions to finish the duel. Using sowrds of reavealing light  then sumon strong fusions and monsters to finish the duel.

deck_excerpt: Idk what a tagline is, so I guess I should just say this deck is based on the Formud Skipper card as a Domain
deck_description:
This deck was made for the Domain Format, based on a deck made by the user Pizza: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/unfinished-deck-312191

Hey, if anyone want's to give this deck a try (I don't have TTS and don't like Untap), just let me know how well it works as I'm testing with it. The idea is similar to pizza's deck except your first goal is always to get out heatsoul, because his draw power helps you set up rituals and fusions. Beyond getting heatsoul out, you can go into either the crusadia or marincess path combos turn 1 or the following turn. Once you have everything set up and you are comfortable with your board presence, you can play some flood gates to keep the board state relatively unchanged. The deck also features lots of stun traps to delay your opponent as you increase your board presence.

 

For some of the main combos, you can refer to Pizza's list, but besides that I'm hoping this version of the deck allows for stronger end boards that you can easily rebuild and recycle without feeling underwhelmed by the deck's power output.

deck_excerpt: Losing with this deck is SPYRAL Mission: Impossible!
deck_description:
I may be a little biased, but I'm fairly certain this is the greatest SPYRAL decklist ever created. Here's the quik card-by-card:

MAIN DECK MONSTERS:

Magicians' Souls is the best starter in the deck. Getting Master Plan in your GY is step 1 of your mission, and this is the best way to get her there. It's on field effect is also great for draw power. You're almost always getting at least 1 draw from sending Big Red, and in the best case scenario you're sending up to 2 of your SPYRAL Mission cards to the GY to set up their effects and draw 2.

Quik-Fix is your main searcher, and ideally what you want to use your normal summon on. It's search effect is a soft once-per-turn (I'll be saying that a lot in this guide) that allows to add any SPYRAL GEAR card and activates on both normal and special summon. Your ideal search target is Big Red, the archetypical Premature Burial, so we can use it to revive Master Plan and start using her search effects ASAP and link both of them off for Double Helix. You can also search out Drone and Last Resort. He also has a GY effect which allows us to discard a card (not really a downside in this deck) to revive it and trigger its effect again in the same turn if Super Agent (or Double Helix) is on the field, but banishes when it leaves the field (but there's a way around that we'll get to later). We would be playing 3 Quik-Fix if we could.

Master Plan is our other searcher. She has a non once-per-turn ignition effect that allows you to search for a SPYRAL MISSION card: Either the spell, SPYRAL MISSION Assault, or the trap, SPYRAL MISSION Rescue, which both have powerful effects that activate in the GY. She also has a hard once-per-turn effect that searches for any SPYRAL monster AND the field spell when she is sent from the field to the GY. 2 is standard because she's bricky, an ideally you want to send her from deck to GY.

Drone allows you to stack the top 3 cards of your opponents deck on normal or special summon, which is crucial for making sure the effects of Double Helix and Super Agent resolve. Ideally you want to search it with the field spell: Resort, or with Master Plan's hard once-per-turn search, then special summon it from the hand by discarding Assault and banishing Assault from the GY. Its 2 other effects are only occasionally useful. 1 Drone is necessary, but personally I think 2 feels right. Builds that play Machine Duplication will opt to play 3.

Super Agent is a free special summon of the hand if you can successfully name the card type of the top card of your opponents deck. Ideally you want to trigger this effect after Drone so you aren't blind guessing. Having Super Agent on board is important because of Quik-Fix's GY effect, but since Double Helix's name is treated as Super Agent while on the field, it's not the end of the world if you can't stick him on board. 1 is necessary, but some people play up to 3.

Sleeper is your main deck boss monster. He must be special summoned by banishing 3 SPYRAL cards from your GY. He's a 2800 body that can pop 1 of your SPYRAL cards (we can get around this) in order to pop 2 of your opponents cards during either players turn. Sleeper is not a necessary inclusion and can be a bit bricky, but I think he's worth the risk.

Last Resort is a monster that equips itself to a SPYRAL monster to give it destruction protection, and targeting protection from your opponent. This card is meant to be played with Sleeper. Sleeper can target the monster Last Resort is eqipped to (usually itself) to pop 2 of your opponents cards with no drawback. Last Resort is a 1-of, and is only good when paired with Sleeper.

We're playing a small Danger engine of 2 Jackalope and 3 Tsuchinoko. 4 reasons why: draw power, link climbing, putting our SPYRAL Mission cards/a bricky Master Plan in the GY, and they are excellent Small World bridges.

MAIN DECK SPELLS/TRAPS:

Small World is the search spell of choice. Where Arf Thou used to be the standard way of searching Magicians' Souls/Quik-Fix, but I find Small World to be the far superior choice. This deck has fantastic bridges. If you plan on trying this deck out, I advise you to take the upload the .ydk to the Small World Deck Optimizer and familliarize yourself with the bridges. 3 copies are necessary.

SPYRAL Resort is an incredible field spell. It gives your SPYRAL monsters targeting protection, and searches a monster on a soft once-per-turn. 3 copies are necessary.

SPYRAL Mission: Assault special summons a monster from the hand. One is necessary to get your plays going.

SPYRAL Mission: Rescue is one of the most important cards in the deck. It revives a SPYRAL monster by banishing itself from the GY. This is the card that will allow you to keep extending your plays until you have a full board. You need 3.

The above 2 cards are ALWAYS meant to be going from your hand to the GY. They are useless on field.

Chicken Game plays SO nicely with this deck. Because Resort is so searchable and Magicians' Souls can send it to the GY to draw a card, there are a multitude of ways to get it off the board. Chicken Game not necessary, but I think the consistency boost is worth the risk.

One For One is great. It's one of the best ways to summon Quik-Fix or Drone from the deck and set up follow-ups and to send an unwanted Master Plan from hand to GY.

Monster Reborn is the universal extender.

I think the rest of the cards in the Main Deck are pretty self explanitory. 1 Terraforming, 2 Ash Blossom, 2 Maxx "C", 2 Called by the Grave. Don't even think about cutting Ash and Maxx "C", you need them as Small World bridges.

EXTRA DECK:

Double Helix is the only archetype specific Extra Deck monster. It must be made using 2 SPYRAL monsters. Ideally you want to use Drone to stack your opponents deck before using the effect, since you're required to correctly call the card type of the top card of your opponent's deck on order to summon a monster from your deck. Usually you'll be using this to summon a Master Plan or Quik-Fix so you can start cycling their effects. It's very important that you leave this card on board until you're done cycling through your Quik-Fix's because you need a card that treats its name as "Super Agent" on board to activate Quik-Fix's GY effect.

Sylvan Princessprite is the sole non-link monster in our Extra Deck. You'll want to make this card with a SPYRAL Quik-Fix that has already used its GY effect to revive itself once. At this point, Quik-Fix would banish itself if it left the field, but Sylvan Princessprite allows us to dodge this by detatching Quik-Fix for cost and place it back in the GY for an extra use. The effect itself isn't hugely important, but it does pay off occasionally.

The Knightmare monsters are very important in this deck, not just because of their generic usefulness, but because they discard your SPYRAL: Mission cards to the GY to allow for follow ups. Barricadeborg Blocker is good for the same reason.

The rest is pretty standard link-spam goodstuff.

Curious can be used to send any card to the GY, most likely Master Plan or a SPYRAL Mission card. If you're making Curious, you're likely using some combination of Linkuriboh, Magicians' Souls, Jackalope and Tsuchinoko. Selene can be made with Master Plan and/or magicians souls for an easy Link-4 with the proper setup. Tri-Gate Wizard is our omni-negate. We can make a 3-4 material Apollousa quite consistently. Accesscode and Underworld Goddess are what we use to clear boards going second. I:P Masquerena and Linkuriboh do what the usually do. Saryuja is pretty win-more but it's cool when it pops-off.

OTHER TECH OPTIONS:

Historically, Machine Duplication has been a pretty powerful tech option in this deck. While Machine Duplication is certainly not as good as it was when Quik-Fix was unlimited, it can still be a pretty explosive card, allowing you to summon 1 additional Quik-Fix from the deck, or putting 2 extra copies of Drone on the board for link plays. Obviously you want to play 3 coplies of Drone if you choose to play Machine Duplication. Personally I'm not a fan because it can lead to a lot of bricky hands due to the overall lack of Machines in the deck.

The Winged-Beast engine is a pretty popular choice. By playing  Lyrilusc - Recital Starling as your Rank 1 and Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty in your Extra Deck, as well as D.D. Crow and Mist Valley Apex Avian in your Main Deck, You can summon Apex Avian during your End Phase for an omni-negate on your opponents turn, while grabbing yourself a D.D Crow in the process. This also gives you the option of playing the incredibly oppressive Harpie's Feather Storm, which can negate monster effects if you have a Winged-Beast monster on the field.

Knightmare Gryphon is another powerful Link-4 this deck can play. Like the other Knightmares, you can use Gryphon to send your SPYRAL Mission cards to the GY in order to trigger their effects. Its effect can be used to set any trap card sent to the GY with Curious: The most popular choices include Anti-Spell Fragrance, Appointer of the Red Lotus, and the aforementioned Harpie's Feather Storm. Gryphon pairs particularly well with the Winged-Beast package.

You can play a copy of Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon in your Extra Deck and Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion in your Main Deck for Synchro plays. Borreload Savage Dragon is the most popular option due to its incredible omni-negate.

If you choose to play any of the above Main Deck Packages, I advise you to cut Sleeper and Last Resort, since they are the brickiest cards in the main package, and arguably the least important.

Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is one of the most difficult to deal with boss monsters in the game with its great battle protection and targeting immunity. It becomes even nastier if you can bring it out on your opponents turn with I:P Masquerena for additional destruction protection.

I didn't have space for it above, but Firewall Dragon is always a good option with it's generic bounce effect. It will always be co-linked to Tri-Gate Wizard at the very least.

Proxy Dragon is the best Link-2 you can play if you want to U-Link with this deck. It's L/R arrows are great and it's incredibly generic, requiring only 2 monsters. The protection effect can be occasionally useful, I've used it to pop Tri-Gate Wizard in order to protect my Apollousa on multiple occasions.

Card Destruction isn't bad in this deck. Obvously it activates the discard effects of Jackalope and Tsuchinoko, as well as putting your SPYRAL Mission cards in the GY, but it can also be used to take the 'Maxx "C" Challenge'. For those unfamilliar, the Maxx "C" Challenge is when you special summon enough monsters in one turn to make your opponent draw more than half of their deck, then resolve Card Destruction to make them discard their entire hand and draw the same number of cards, instantly decking them out, resulting in an FTK. Going first against a 40 card deck, this is done by special summoning 18 times after Maxx "C" resolves, something that SPYRALS are certainly capable of doing under the right circumstances. It's gimmicky and I wouldn't recommend it, but it's an option.

And of course, you can always cut cards like Chicken Game for extra interruptions and hand traps.

CONCLUSION:

The last thing I want to say about this deck: BE MINDFUL OF THE TIMER. This deck is infamous for its incredibly long combos, and even though I can play the deck at a reasonable speed, I will often pass turn with less than 30 seconds remaining on the clock, and I've timed out/been forced to pass on a sub-optimal board many times. Keep in mind that your time doesn't increase until the end of your opponents turn, so you will need to manage that small amount of time well when the clock passes back over to you.

Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Warriors of light descended from the brilliant stars in the sky
deck_description:
Do you like Loops with Insane swarming? Do you enjoy the concept of Space Medieval Knights? Then I may have the perfect Deck for you!

KONAMI BANNED ARTIFACT SCYTHE SO IGNORE ALL MENTIONS OF IT, DAGDA OR AZALEA. I REPLACED THEM WITH TELLARKNIGHT CONSTELLAR, LYNA AND BAGOOSKA RESPECTIVELY. THE COMBO IN THE VIDEO REMAINS THE SAME BUT YOU ARE GOING TO SUMMON LYNA INSTEAD OF DAGDA AND YOU WILL END ON AVRAMAX UNLESS YOU WANT TO COPE AND PLAY Artifact Moralltach .

Main Deck:

Part 1: Monsters 

Chapter 1: The 88 Constellations (Satellars)

  • Satellarknight Deneb - Behold! This is your Monster searcher. He doesn't do much besides it but, its something you want to get on board ASAP.
  • Satellarknight Unukalhai - Acting as a Foolish Burial / Foolish Burial Goods for the entire Archetype, Unukalhai is an important for your combos, being able to foolish cards like Tellarknight Altea who can summon himself back to your field to blow up cards or putting combo pieces that can be retrieved with Satellarknight Altair or Tellarknight Constellar 's effects. 
  • Tellarknight Lyra - Very important part of the Deck, summoning herself if you summoned a "-Tellar" and adding a "Tellarknight" Spell for you, which the best choice would be Satellarknight Skybridge which can shuffle her back and bring in a new "-Tellar" and can trigger Tellarknight Altea in your GY.
  • Satellarknight Vega - Summons a "Tellar" from your hand, you have better normal summons, but its a free R4NK 100% of the time.
  • Satellarknight Sirius - Helps in the grindgames to recycle back your Extra Deck Monsters, you want to summon this guy using Stellarknight Delteros floating effect.
  • Satellarknight Altair - One of the most important cards, being able to revive any of your dead monsters, which you want to most of the time use to loop Stellarknight Delteros to summon more "-Tellars" from your deck, which can be done up to 3 times per turn. Other than that Altair is an incredible swarming tool since your GY will be packed with a lot of different names.
  • Tellarknight Altea - Free summon from GY, one of the best target for Satellarknight Unukalhai , summons itself back from GY popping cards when it does, which can be done in the opponent's turn with Tellarknight Ptolemaeus to pop some problem card/combo starter.
  • Honorable Mentions: Constellar Sheratan and Constellar Caduceus - Sheratan is your banish target for Tellarknight Constellar Caduceus which will search Constellar Caduceus whose effect allows him to be special summoned to the field and search a "Constellar" Spell/Trap which can be Constellar Star Chart for draws or Tellarknight Constellar to combo. 

Part 2: Spells

Chapter 1: The weaver girl and the cowherd

  • Satellarknight Skybridge - This card is just incredible, it can be searched by Tellarknight Lyra , it turns a dead "Tellar" on the field into any of your other "Tellars", it also helps dodging negates like Effect Veiler or Infinite Impermanence .
  • Tellarknight Constellar - Their newest support lets you summon a "Tellar" from hand or grave, which can be a useful extension and can revive the targets sent  by Satellarknight Unukalhai . Its other effect is to turn your "Tellar" or "Constellar" XYZs into another one of different Rank, helping you get to Stellarknight Constellar Diamond faster.
  • Constellar Star Chart - Free draws when overlaying into Constellar Pleiades .

Part 3: Extra Deck

Chapter 1: Bright Constellations

  • Tellarknight Constellar Caduceus - The new guy, fetching dead "Tellar" and "Constellar" cards from your GY to add back to your hand, and his detach effect can copy one of your "Tellars" or "Constellars" by banishing them and detaching one material. This guy can be overlayed into Constellar Ptolemy M7 and then Tellarknight Constellar 'ed into Tellarknight Ptolemaeus .
  • Stellarknight Triverr - Mass bouncing, puts your continuous spells back to your hand, and he hass a hand-rip effect. He is somewhat obsolete now after the Deck moved on from Crackdown and Call of the Haunted .
  • Stellarknight Delteros - On the other hand, can pop a card, which most of the time it will be himself, when this card is sent to the GY non-opt summons a "Tellar" from your Deck or Hand, so besides blowing himself with his effect you can, summon Satellarknight Altair to revive him, link him away to summon something else, and then summoning him back with Tellarknight Constellar to make Stellarknight Constellar Diamond . This one just got better with time, not many decks can brag about having a non opt summon from Deck.
  • Tellarknight Ptolemaeus and Darktellarknight Batlamyus - Both serve the same purpose, being able to make diamond in your opponent's turn, but Ptolemaeus is way better at doing this job.
  • Constellar Pleiades and Constellar Ptolemy M7 - Both bounce stuff which can include your dead monsters in the case of M7 and backrow for Pleiades.
  • Stellarknight Constellar Diamond - Stops things from getting in and out of the GY, and negates Dark monsters.

Example of a Combo:

 

Final Thoughts: Pretty baller deck, 10/10 space people looping me! The support made the deck go from set pass 5 die next turn to a swarm heavy deck that can do pretty insane loops.

deck_excerpt: The strongest anti-GY Synchro strategy is here with PUNK Bystial!
deck_description:
Dying for the sins of the current meta decks - Tearlaments and Spright, PUNK lost two key combo cards - Halqifibrax and Chaos Ruler. Effectively cut off from most of it's combo lines, PUNK has been reduced to a shell of it's former self. The current cards that counter Tearlaments and Spright also happen to counter PUNK as well, since PUNK use the graveyard as well leaving them vulnerable to Ishizu GY-shufflers and anti-GY floodgates like Necrovalley.

 

Losing its two MVPs and countered by common meta techs, PUNK can only turn to incorporate other archetypes and enablers to pack a competitive punch and thus I present to you - PUNK Bystial!

On top of PUNK's regular gameplan of drawing multiple cards and summoning Synchro boss monsters, Bystial adds free bodies (more level 6s and 8s to sync with!) on board, more resources in hand (Branded Regained/Magnumhut), additional interruptions (Branded Beast/anti-GY) and a way to counter those pesky Tearlaments that dominate the metagame!

Surprisingly, with the anti-GY powerhouse that Bystial provides combined with the draw power and synchro shenanigans that PUNK enables create a surprisingly competent deck - a partnership able to combat the strongest this "Tear 0" meta has to offer!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

This deck is a variant of my "Pure PUNK" deck guide I made last year, so If you want a complete guide with all the combos, tips and gameplant, visit my Pure PUNK article linked here.
 
Small World is amazing since it replaces a brick in your hand to add one of your starters! The following are Small World search combos:
  • Activate Small World -> Any Dark Bystial/Effect Veiler -> D.D. Crow -> Obtain PUNK Ogre Dance (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Psy-Frame Gamma -> Nibiru -> Obtain PUNK Foxy Tune (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Ogre -> PUNK Deer Note -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner (starts PUNK combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> PUNK Foxy Tune -> Effect Veiler -> Bystial Lubellion (starts Bystial combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner -> Effect Veiler -> Bystial Lubellion (starts Bystial combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> D.D. Crow -> Effect Veiler -> Bystial Lubellion (starts Bystial combo line)
  • Activate Small World -> Any Level 3 Punk Tuner -> Effect Veiler -> Ash Blossom/Ghost Belle (I usually do this if I have all combo pieces already)
There are more Small World combos out in this deck and that can be included in, but these are the ones I primarily use. Feel free to experiment and add more!

Some notable tips on this deck are:
  • Any Bystial + Level 3 PUNK Tuner can synchro summon Shenshen. A mini "macro cosmos," Shenshen auto-wins vs. common GY reliant decks that use the field alot like Runick, Naturia and Tearlament.
  • PUNK Jam Extreme Session can trigger Branded Regained's draw effect. When you use Extreme Session's summon from hand effect, banish a Light/Dark PUNK monster, and Regained grants you an additional draw. Regained + Extreme Session means you can draw 3 cards in one turn!
  • Bystial Lubellion + Level 3 Punk Tuner can make Psychic End Punisher, or alternatively, you can also make Punk Amazing Dragon, which grants you removal/extension options if you want to play offensively. Lubellion + Psy-Frame Gear Gamma (summoned with Emergency Teleport) are also perfect for making Baronne!
  • Vs. decks like Floowandereeze that don't use Light/Dark monsters and don't need monsters in the GY, just side out your entire Bystial package for the anti-Floo cards in your side deck.
  • A prime discard target for PUNK Foxy Tune is Bystial Saronir. Sending Saronir to the GY turns on your entire Bystial engine since Saronir is a foolish burial for it's archetype.
  • Bystials break boards very easily. Discarding Lubellion -> Druiswurm, then summing Lubellion from the GY removes 1 monster on the field and give you a 2500 beatstick on field, without your normal summon. Try all of these actions to bait out negates, interruption and floodgates before comboing off with your PUNKs!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!
KURIIIIIBOHHH'S
The first archetype is always the best

deck_excerpt: Pure Ogdoadics that actually win games in master duel BO1 format.
deck_description:
The goal of this deck (most Yu-Gi-Oh decks in general) is to set up your grave yard while keeping your opponent from doing the same thing.

 

Best Matchups:

*Other Non-Meta decks

*Most Rogue decks

*People that believe reptiles decks are not good.

*Any deck that uses the graveyard to discard/ special summon monsters.

*Any one that says yes to your "draw backs" (ie opponent gets to special summon from grave because you brought out Keurse. They think they're +1 for free but they're really not)

 

Worst match ups...

T1-Decks you can beat them often but not as often as you'd like. They're too consistent and 1 card can turn the game in their favor. Trust me... they have A LOT  of cards that fit that criteria but you shouldn't just auto surrender. I've beat Despia, Sword Soul, Plunder Patrol & the like plenty of times but it's not easy. Not easy at all. it's like you're starting with 5 card's & they're starting with 15. but you can beat them if you're creative/lucky enough.

*Banish decks (Flow, Metaphys and the like) Auto F6. don't waste your time unless you top deck MST or Harpie to kill the macro or dimension shifter. If they use the banish hand trap, F6.

*Pendulms- Pendulums don't use the grave yard, don't let them go 1st (F6) unless you have 2 or more of these: Ash,Veiler, Imperm or Maxx "C".

if you go 1st you should be fine majority of the time; Assuming you don't brick or misplay your assets.

 

 

Game Plan:

 

Going 1st:

1. Bait the hand trap(s) - use Nunu or Nauya's search effect to Ash check. They better Ash this or its basically a free win for you if they dont have ash at all. If you get Called by or DD Crow'd you can't do a full set up turn 1 (very bad against tier 1 decks. Other non meta/rogue decks, you should live.)

2. If you got Ashed, then Special Summon Nunu from grave yard (GY). If not, send Zohah to GY. Use Zohah's effect to add it to your hand and send anything with more than 4 stars to the GY or Sinister Serpent (Will be called SS from now on). If you have Nauya, use its search for Zohah (Keurse if you have Zohah or Nunu already in hand = Free win) If you have a snake rain that resolves, you'd better orgasm because that a Free win x 5.

3. Normal Summon Zohah and XYZ summon into King of Feral Imps for next hand trap check. it doesn't matter if they negate the search effect (you don't want Nunu banished when it leaves the field so you detach it as xyz material). If they didn't Negate the search effect, this can mean 3 things:

*They know the decks actual choke points (extremely bad!!!)

*They don't have anymore handtrap(s) = free win 

* They are unfamilliar with the deck = free win

4. If, Feral Imp King gets negated, fret not, you saved your resources from getting banished and can recycle the same play next turn.

Your well-placed hand traps should hold you down with your feral imp in defense mode. BUT... before you do this, you need to check your grave yard for the following:

1...Keurse

&

2... Nauya

 

if these two are in the GY, you don't have to end turn; keep going.

5. Tribute Feral Imp King & summon Keurse from GY (WARNING SERIOUS CHOKE POINT). DO NOT special summon keurse unless you're CERTAIN you can bring out Nauya. If not it's a brick it could spell the end for you. if they special summon what every they wan't from the GY, it doesnt matter since its effects are negated, you need to bring out Nauya from your GY. Once Nauya is summoned to your field, you search for either Water Lilly or Serpent Strike.

6. If you already have the queen in the GY, dont get Water Lilly. Get Serpent Strike, Send Keurse to the GY to summon Zohah but don't activate its effect. Now you should have nothing but 2 level 4's on the field. Zohah and Nauya. If you couldn't get feral Imp out earlier, you can get it out now. If you did & sent it to GY for Keurse no worries, tribute summon queen from GY using Zohah & Nauya as materials. Nauya should be banished by Keurse's effect but you can recycle cards from the banished area some what with Aelirtt's effect. you don't want to have to do this though it can back fire if you have to use him to get you key cards unbanished like Zohah constantly. Don't banish too much & try not to get banished too much.

7. Ogdoadic Queen should be on the field & you should be activating Zohah's effect.

8. Add Ogdoadice king to your hand then send it to grave yard. If your oppent is a dummy, he'll discard a monster card in which you can do 1 or both of these:

1... Special Summon King from GY for free.

&

2... Send Ogdoadic Over lord to the GY for free if you chose Serpent Strike over Water Lilly. If you chose Water Lilly, no worries. Queen will summon Zohah from GY next turn when your opponent searches and discards a card. if he doesn't king will make him discard anyway so you opponent can lose card advantage really easily with these two on the field. If they out your queen, you cant summon Zohah from grave but you can -1 their hand off a search with king which can be clutch 7/10 times. If they out your king, then just summon him back when they discard to grave using queen. if they don't out one or the other its GG's. If they summon from rave while queen is up you can send anything from their field to GY. That's huge!!!

 

8. If a monster is sent from the field to the grave, you search or recycle your King of Imps with King's effect. Use, king & queen's effect to sabotage your oppenent while you set up your own GY for next turn. If done correctly, they'll surrender or have spotty board that really fickle. If you have hand traps like a Maxx "C", they'll definitely surrender.

9. Let's say sheet went south & you need to draw the out. That's where the clean up crew comes in. You can use queen to over lord from GY if he's there or search Water lilly with Keurse combo next turn to send him from deck & summon him that way. then he gets out, he wipes all monsters on the field that didn't come from the GY. its a hard once per summon so you'll have to send him back to the GY if you can end the game after his effect went off. if he cleared the field; you should have king (2500) queen (2700) & overlord (3100) to One-Turn-Kill (8300 atk dmg).

10. If not, you're problably up against a T1 Deck. In that case, you're gonna need Aleirtt and the other monsters from your extra deck. Most Games you shouldn't have to do this, but Yu-Gi-Oh just wants to keep making super consistent decks that pull plays out of their butt from no where. So here we go,

you're problably going to lose to time trying to recover the materials needed to build your board back after a few rounds of trades so don't be too upset. Yu-GI-Oh hates reptiles so just be happy you can at least compete with a T1 deck. If you enough time to get a board up, i'll leave the extra deck options to your imagination. Use the extra deck monsters i've recommended in a creative manner & you will come out of top 6-7/10 match ups in master duel provided you didn't lose to a time out!

ENJOY!!!

deck_description:
Little dumb blurb thing


Well then.
This was an interesting revelation, a (somewhat) consistent Ghostrick OTK.
Never thought I'd see the day. 
Although these monsters lack much power,
They come together in the spooky hour. 
And while no-one plays this archetype,
Those who do will never gripe. 
as these guys are so fu***** fun,
Most cards will never be run. 
And so, I open the gates
Where the spooky scary (skeletons) monsters wait.
And I invite you, to step into the bullpen.

(Yes I know I sound insane, the two first ones rhymed so I went with it.)

Anyway, Ghostricks are my favorite archetype, I love creepy victorian, gothic, styles, so naturally I love these guys. I know they suck, but... I have to play these guys, like... just look at them!!

Strategy

 

Adventurer Token and Wandering Gryphon Rider are a 1 card 4000 atk duo and negate. After you get those out, all you need is a single ghostrick XYZ, you can climb into Ghostrick Angel of Mischief. Detach the XYZ on Angel, and get a Ghostrick Shot to revive the detached XYZ, climb it back into Angel, and you have an 8000 ATK board. If you need to, you can put a Ghostrick monster in the grave for Fateful Adventure to get Gryphon back if you had to get rid of it. 

if you have questions, put them below, I'll try and answer them! 
GLHF! :)

deck_excerpt: When the samurais collide with the springy machines!
deck_description:
Superheavy Samurai adds a new feel to springans. Using one card can bring out an insanely powerful board along with getting your springans combo. Here's how the line goes:

Activate Waukaushi to special summon itself and activate Benkei, Benkei add piercer, normal summon piercer, make the link, piercer add wagon, link discard wagon and special summon wagon in defense mode, wagon's effect to add peacemaker, peacemaker equip onto the link, peacemaker special summon scales, scales special summon piercer. Link wagon and piercer into ballista, ballista add box, piercer add bike, box add general coral, bike add piercer, link off ballista and Waukaushi into Genius, pendulum summon box, piercer, and waukashi, genius add regulus, link piercer and waukashi into apollousa, piercer add soulgaia, special summon soulgaia, xyz into merry using box and gaia, merry send sargas, xyz into champion sargas, champion add tallyho, tallyho detach 2, search rockey and special summon rockey and regular sargas from graveyard, rockey add any springans in gy to hand, xyz into dweller using rockey and scales, and to top it off, special summon regulus.

Chironex uses a "Jellyfish-themed WATER" Deck, primarily focused on swarm and burn tactics, centered around "Number 4: Stealth Kragen" and "Kragen Spawns". I added Mermails to complete this deck.

Hello all, 

 

this is the decklist you can see in my video. In the video you can also see replays so you can understand the combos but I mention briefly what it's about.

The whole deck spams you Rank 4 XYZ monsters. The Lunalight Engine is especially good for this because you can bounce Lunalight Tiger  so often and thus extend them properly. Also you are able to play with Raidraptor - Force Strix  which allows you to go to Number F0: Utopic Draco Future  very easily. The deck has become much more consistent and has a stronger endboard in the end.

 

In the video you can see Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring  and two Fire Formation - Tenki . You can actually cut ash and replace it with a third Fire Formation - Tenki  and Called by the Grave 

 

If you like the decklist or the video feel free to leave a like and if you want to support me feel free to leave a subscription. :)

You already know how it goes,

Three Chicken Games for -3000, three Pseudo Spaces for other -3000, get yourself to 2000 LP or less (easier if you get Piri Reis Map in your starting hand), set Fuhma Shurikens and play Reversal Quiz. Deck even gets through Ash Blossom on one draw from RML (happened numerous times). Only way to lose is if your Reversal Quiz happens to be on the bottom of the deck (you can avoid it by saving Pot of Duality for the last 3 cards), or if you brick really hard (Magical Mallets help a lot).

Have fun playing the game by yourself (opponents also quit mid-game a lot) and climbing ranks. Last night I played 3 hours by myself, always going first with no responses from my enemies, had the time of my life! Enjoy.
